{"id":"1211.6001","submitter":"Antonio Padilla","authors":"Clare Burrage, Nemanja Kaloper, and Antonio Padilla","title":"Strong Coupling and Bounds on the Graviton Mass in Massive Gravity","comments":"v3: typos corrected, conclusions unchanged","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.111.021802","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th astro-ph.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The theory of a single massive graviton has a cutoff much below its Planck\nscale, because the extra modes from the graviton multiplet involve higher\nderivative self-interactions, controlled by a scale convoluted from the small\ngraviton mass. Generically, these correct the propagator by environmental\neffects. The resulting effective cutoff depends on the environmental parameters\nand the graviton mass. Requiring the theory to be perturbative down to ${\\cal\nO}(1) mm$, we derive bounds on the graviton mass, corresponding to $\\gtrsim\n{\\cal O}(1) meV$ for the generic case, and somewhat weaker bounds in cases of\nfine-tuning. In all cases the mass is required to be much too large for the\ntheory to conform with GR at cosmological distances. Similar results also hold\nin quartic and quintic Galileon theory.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 26 Nov 2012 15:59:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 26 Dec 2012 20:28:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 14 May 2013 12:20:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-08-09"}
